edu.kit.joana.ifc.sdg.util

Class JavaType

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.kit.joana.ifc.sdg.util.JavaType

  • public class JavaType
extends java.lang.Object
    This class represents java types and provides methods to parse a java type from a string. Allowed strings have to meet one of the following formats:
    • human-readable:

      <typeHR> ::= <baseTypeHR>([])* where

      <baseTypeHR> ::= <primitiveTypeHR>| <fqRefTypeHR>

      <primitiveTypeHR> ::= void|boolean|byte|char|short|int|long|float|double

      <fqRefTypeHR> ::= (<packageName>(.<packageName>)*.)?<className>

    • bytecode format:

      <typeBC> ::= ([)*<baseTypeBC> where

      <baseTypeBC> ::= <primitiveTypeBC>|<fqRefTypeBC>

      <primitiveTypeBC> ::= V|C|Z|B|C|S|I|J|F|D

      <fqRefTypeBC> ::= L(<packageName>(\/<packageName>)*\/)?<className>;

    <packageName> and <className> represent allowed package and class names, respectively, in Java.
    Author:
    Martin Mohr

        public static JavaType parseSingleTypeFromString(java.lang.String s,
                                 JavaType.Format f)
        Parse a string into a single type. Depending on the given format, the string will either be interpreted as bytecode-style or human-readable style.
        Parameters:
        s - string to parse
        f - format indicating how to interpret the given string
        Returns:
        JavaType object representing the java type described by the given string

      • parseSingleTypeFromString

        public static JavaType parseSingleTypeFromString(java.lang.String s)
        Parse a string into a single type. Since no format is given, the right style of notation is guessed. It is assumed, that the given string does not denote a primitive type.

        If no or both the human-readable and the bytecode formats are applicable, then null is returned.

        Parameters:
        s - string to parse
        Returns:
        JavaType object representing the java type described by the given string, null if given string is neither in human-readable style nor in bytecode style or if both styles are possible.
